elements.content: A one-dimensional coordination polymer (1D CP), [Cd­(bpe)­(p-brba)2] n (1), has been synthesized by the slow diffusion method keeping the mixture of Cd­(NO3)2·6H2O and 1,2-bis­(4-pyridyl)­ethylene (bpe) ligand along with para-bromobenzoic acid (p-brba) in the dark. Interestingly, the compound 1 undergoes a single-crystal to single-crystal (SCSC) photochemical [2 + 2] cycloaddition reaction to generate dimerized 1D CP [Cd­(rctt-tpcb)1/2(p-brba)2] n (2) [rctt-tpcb = rctt-tetrakis­(4-pyridyl)­cyclobutane]. As a result, π···π stacking interactions among p-brba ligands of adjacent chains have been removed in the dimerized product. This structural transformation has a significant effect on the conductivity of the materials.

elements.content:
Single-crystal to single-crystal structural transformation of 1D coordination polymer (CP) to dimerized 1D CP, which impacts the electrical conductivity and Schottky nature of the material.

Published as part of a Crystal Growth and Design virtual special issue on Structure Property Relationship in Crystalline Solids

Introduction

Solid-state single-crystal to single-crystal (SCSC) structural transformations attains an environmentally benign green concept, because it is devoid of using ecologically harmful organic solvents. In this regard, topochemical [2 + 2] photodimerization has attracted immense interest among the researchers working in the field of solid-state chemistry. The key factor of photodimerization reaction is to align the olefinic double bonds following the Schmidt criteria. This can be achieved by several factors, such as π···π stacking interaction, aurophillic and argentophillic interactions, counteranion effects, etc. MacGillivray et al. developed an elegant method to align the olefinic double bonds in cocrystals for the synthesis of tailor-made cyclobutanes or ladderanes via photochemical [2 + 2] cycloaddition reaction. Vittal and co-workers employed the crystal engineering principle to align olefin bond pairs in coordination polymers (CPs) for topochemical photodimerization. Recently, successful attempts have been made by many groups to utilize this photodimerization reaction in various potential applications. In regard to the application, we have also reported the impact of photochemical structural transformation on the electrical conductivity of a one-dimensional coordination polymer (1D CP). However, to establish this concept, we wanted to explore more on the device application using various systems. Hence, we have employed the frequently used ditopic olefinic ligand 1,2-bis­(4-pyridyl)­ethylene (bpe) for the fabrication of CPs.

Introduction

Solid-state single-crystal to single-crystal (SCSC) structural transformations attains an environmentally benign green concept, because it is devoid of using ecologically harmful organic solvents. elements.content: Our group is mainly involved in the fabrication of 1D or 2D CPs, which would undergo supramolecular aggregations to from higher dimensional networks using monodonor pyridyl ligands projected from the frameworks. The supramolecular assembly offers a congenial environment toward charge transport through a space or “hopping” mechanism. Recently, efforts are being paid to fabricate suitable CPs, which show semiconducting behavior and Schottky diode application. As a part of our goal, herein, we are able to synthesize a 1D CP [Cd­(bpe)­(p-brba)2] n (1) using bpe spacer and monodentate para-bromobenzoic acid (p-brba) ligands. The 1D chains are aggregated via Br···π and π···π stacking interactions to fabricate a 3D network. Interestingly, compound 1 is photoreactive and undergoes SCSC photochemical [2 + 2] cycloaddition to form dimerized 1D CP [Cd­(rctt-tpcb)1/2(p-brba)2] n (2) [rctt-tpcb = rctt-tetrakis­(4-pyridyl)­cyclobutane]. Due to this solid-state structural transformation, π···π stacking interactions among p-brba ligands of adjacent chains have remained absent in the dimerized product, which leads to the reduction in electrical conductivity value after photodimerization. In our earlier study, we have reported that the conductivity value enhances upon photodimerization due to the increase in the extent of π···π interactions. Therefore, these results are in accordance with those observed in our reported material.

Elemental analysis (carbon, hydrogen, and nitrogen) was performed on a PerkinElmer 240C elemental analyzer. The infrared spectrum in KBr (4500–500 cm–1) was recorded using a PerkinElmer FT-IR spectrum RX1 spectrometer. elements.clean_text:
Experimental Section

Materials and Methods

The chemicals purchased for the synthesis were reagent grade and were used without further purification. Elemental analysis (carbon, hydrogen, and nitrogen) was performed on a PerkinElmer 240C elemental analyzer. The infrared spectrum in KBr (4500-500 cm-1) was recorded using a PerkinElmer FT-IR spectrum RX1 spectrometer. Photodimerization reaction was carried out using a Luzchem photoreactor (8 W UVA lamps) at ~350 nm for 30 min at room temperature.

Syntheses of Compounds

A solution of bpe (0.036 g, 0.2 mmol) in MeOH (2 mL) was slowly and carefully layered to a solution of Cd(NO3)2⋅4H2O (0.062 g, 0.2 mmol), in H2O (2 mL) using 2 mL of buffer solution of DMF followed by layering of H2 p-brba (0. 0.040 g, 0.2 mmol) neutralized with Et3N (0.021 g, 0.2 mmol) in 2 mL of EtOH. Then, the resulting reaction mixture was kept in a dark cabinet. The colorless block-shaped crystals of [Cd(bpe)(p-brba)2] n  (1) were obtained after a week (0.097 g, yield 70%). Elemental analysis (%) calcd for C26H18Br2CdN2O4: C, 44.95; H, 2.61; N, 4.03; found: C, 44.7; H, 2.4; N, 4.2. elements.content: Single crystals of compounds 1 and 2 having suitable dimension were used for data collection using a Bruker SMART APEX II diffractometer equipped with graphite-monochromated Mo Kα radiation (λ = 0.71073 Å). The molecular structure was solved using the SHELXT 2014/4 structure solution program. Least squares refinements of all reflections within the hkl range −15 ≤ h ≤ 15, −15 ≤ k ≤ 15, −22 ≤ l ≤ 22 were used to figure out the unit cell parameters and crystal-orientation matrices. The collected data (I > 2σ­(I)) was integrated by using the SAINT program, and the absorption correction was done by SADABS. Non-hydrogen atoms were refined by the help of anisotropic thermal parameters. All of the hydrogen atoms were placed in their geometrically perfect positions and constrained to ride on their parent atoms. The crystallographic data for 1 and 2 are summarized in Table S1, and selected bond lengths and bond angles are given in Tables S2–S4.
elements.clean_text:
General X-ray Crystallography

Single crystals of compounds 1 and 2 having suitable dimension were used for data collection using a Bruker SMART APEX II diffractometer equipped with graphite-monochromated Mo Kα radiation (λ = 0.71073 Å). The molecular structure was solved using the SHELXT 2014/4 structure solution program. Least squares refinements of all reflections within the hkl range -15 ≤ h ≤ 15, -15 ≤ k ≤ 15, -22 ≤ l ≤ 22 were used to figure out the unit cell parameters and crystal-orientation matrices. The collected data (I > 2σ(I)) was integrated by using the SAINT program, and the absorption correction was done by SADABS. Non-hydrogen atoms were refined by the help of anisotropic thermal parameters. All of the hydrogen atoms were placed in their geometrically perfect positions and constrained to ride on their parent atoms. The crystallographic data for 1 and 2 are summarized in Table S1, and selected bond lengths and bond angles are given in Tables S2-S4.

elements.content: To fabricate the Schottky device, we have taken fluorine doped tin oxide (FTO) coated glass substrates and cleaned them with 2-isopropanol, acetone, and distilled water in sequence. In the meantime, we have prepared the dispersed homogeneous medium of the synthesized material and the dimethylformamide (DMF) is chosen as a medium to make the dispersed medium (as per the concentration of 4 mg/μL). Then, the dispersed medium is spin coated onto the FTO coated glass at 800 rpm for 2 min to produce the film. After drying the film in a vacuum chamber, the aluminum (Al) metal is deposited onto the film using the vacuum coating unit. The effective area of the fabricated devices is controlled with the help of a shadow mask. We have applied a bias voltage of −1 to +1 V to the fabricated device under ambient conditions in the dark and investigated its electrical properties using a Keithley 2635B sourcemeter.
elements.clean_text:
Device Fabrication and Characterization

To fabricate the Schottky device, we have taken fluorine doped tin oxide (FTO) coated glass substrates and cleaned them with 2-isopropanol, acetone, and distilled water in sequence. In the meantime, we have prepared the dispersed homogeneous medium of the synthesized material and the dimethylformamide (DMF) is chosen as a medium to make the dispersed medium (as per the concentration of 4 mg/μL). Then, the dispersed medium is spin coated onto the FTO coated glass at 800 rpm for 2 min to produce the film. After drying the film in a vacuum chamber, the aluminum (Al) metal is deposited onto the film using the vacuum coating unit. The effective area of the fabricated devices is controlled with the help of a shadow mask. We have applied a bias voltage of -1 to +1 V to the fabricated device under ambient conditions in the dark and investigated its electrical properties using a Keithley 2635B sourcemeter.

elements.content: Theoretical calculations were carried out via the Gaussian 09 package. Here, the DFT-B3LYP hybrid functional was used. The LanL2DZ basis set was assigned for all of the elements present in the structural architecture. To constrain the electronic transitions, the time-dependent density functional theory (TDDFT) formalism of the compounds was performed. Gauss sum calculations were performed to calculate the fractional contribution of the coordination polymer.
elements.clean_text:
Theoretical Calculation

Theoretical calculations were carried out via the Gaussian 09 package. Here, the DFT-B3LYP hybrid functional was used. The LanL2DZ basis set was assigned for all of the elements present in the structural architecture. To constrain the electronic transitions, the time-dependent density functional theory (TDDFT) formalism of the compounds was performed. Gauss sum calculations were performed to calculate the fractional contribution of the coordination polymer.

elements.content: Compound 1 has been synthesized in the dark by slow diffusion of bpe and p-brba in ethanol into an aqueous solution of Cd­(NO3)2·6H2O and Et3N in H2O/MeOH using DMF buffer. However, compound 2 is prepared by photochemical [2 + 2] cycloaddition reaction exposing the crystals of 1 under UV irradiation (). X-ray crystallographic experiments reveal that 1 crystallizes in the triclinic space group P 1̅ with Z = 2. The compound has a 1D ladder polymeric structure. The asymmetric unit of 1 consists of a Cd­(II) center having a distorted pentagonal bipyramid geometry. The equatorial plane is described by two oxygen atoms from a chelating carboxylate group and three oxygen atoms from a μ2-chelating/bridging carboxylate group (Scheme S1, Supporting Information). The axial sites are occupied by two nitrogen atoms from two bpe ligands. Here, two μ2-chelating/bridging carboxylate groups bridge a pair of Cd­(II) centers to form a dinuclear [Cd2(μ2-O2CC)2] secondary building unit (SBU) such that the bpe pairs are aligned parallel with face-to-face π···π interactions (Figure S1, Supporting Information). The distance between the center of the CC is 3.800(7) Å in 1. A crystallographic inversion center is present in the middle of the [Cd2(μ2-O2CC)2] ring with a Cd···Cd distance of 3.8742(4) Å in 1. The SBUs are interconnected by a pair of bpe ligands to form a 1D ladder polymer (a). Further, the 1D ladder polymer undergoes Br···π and π···π interactions to generate a three-dimensional (3D) supramolecular structure (Figures S2 and S3, Supporting Information).
elements.clean_text:
Results and Discussion

Structural Descriptions

Compound 1 has been synthesized in the dark by slow diffusion of bpe and p-brba in ethanol into an aqueous solution of Cd(NO3)2⋅6H2O and Et3N in H2O/MeOH using DMF buffer. However, compound 2 is prepared by photochemical [2 + 2] cycloaddition reaction exposing the crystals of 1 under UV irradiation (). X-ray crystallographic experiments reveal that 1 crystallizes in the triclinic space group P      1̅     with Z = 2. The compound has a 1D ladder polymeric structure. The asymmetric unit of 1 consists of a Cd(II) center having a distorted pentagonal bipyramid geometry. The equatorial plane is described by two oxygen atoms from a chelating carboxylate group and three oxygen atoms from a μ2-chelating/bridging carboxylate group (Scheme S1, Supporting Information). The axial sites are occupied by two nitrogen atoms from two bpe ligands. Here, two μ2-chelating/bridging carboxylate groups bridge a pair of Cd(II) centers to form a dinuclear [Cd2(μ2-O2CC)2] secondary building unit (SBU) such that the bpe pairs are aligned parallel with face-to-face π⋅⋅⋅π interactions (Figure S1, Supporting Information). The distance between the center of the CC is 3.800(7) Å in 1. A crystallographic inversion center is present in the middle of the [Cd2(μ2-O2CC)2] ring with a Cd⋅⋅⋅Cd distance of 3.8742(4) Å in 1. The SBUs are interconnected by a pair of bpe ligands to form a 1D ladder polymer (a). Further, the 1D ladder polymer undergoes Br⋅⋅⋅π and π⋅⋅⋅π interactions to generate a three-dimensional (3D) supramolecular structure (Figures S2 and S3, Supporting Information).

elements.content: Here, the nonbonding distance between the double bonds of a pair of bpe ligands is congenial for photochemical [2 + 2] cycloaddition in the solid state following the Schmidt criteria (<4.2 Å). UV irradiation of single crystals of 1 for half an hour reveals the formation of 100% dimerized products, as evident from 1H NMR spectra. The 1H NMR spectrum in d 6-DMSO shows the complete disappearance of the peak corresponding to olefinic protons (δ = 7.53) and appearance of cyclobutane protons (δ = 4.65) of rctt-tetrakis­(4-pyridyl)­cyclobutane (Figures S7 and S8, Supporting Information). Hence, the irradiated single crystal of 1 was selected for single-crystal X-ray data collection. The single-crystal X-ray crystallographic analysis of photodimerized product of 1, [Cd­(rctt-tpcb)1/2(p-brba)2] n (2), exhibits the formation of a new bond across the olefinic bonds. As a result, two pyridyl rings become no more parallel and diverge from the cyclobutane ring. Therefore, the Cd···Cd distance increases from 3.8742(4) Å in 1 to 4.102(1) Å in 2. In addition, π···π stacking interactions among p-brba ligands of adjacent chains have completely been destroyed. The centroid–centroid distance has been increased from 3.718(3) Å in 1 to 6.964–6.978 Å in 2 ().

elements.content: We have studied the current density–voltage (J–V) characteristics of the fabricated devices under dark conditions; see a. Both of the characteristic curves show rectifying behavior; however, the rectification ratio of the compound 1 based diode is higher than that of 2. Moreover, the Ohmic conductivity of the compound 1 based diode is derived as 567 times higher than the other device, which is quite significant from the view of optoelectronic application. Therefore, the notable enhancement of conductivity for compound 1 has inspired us to find the parameters related to the potential ability of the Schottky diode. In this regard, we have employed the thermionic emission (TE) theory to find out the device parameters. According to the TE theory, the current density can be written as J = J 0 [ exp ( q V D η K T ) − 1 ] where J 0 = A A * T 2 exp ( − q ϕ B K T ) where J 0, q, k, T, η, A*, and ΦB denote the saturation current, electronic charge, Boltzmann constant, temperature, ideality factor, Richardson constant, and potential barrier height, respectively. The Richardson constant is considered as 1.20 × 106 A K–2 m–2.

The series resistance and ideality factor are derived from the slope and intercept of the dV/d ln J vs J plot, whereas the potential barrier height is evaluated from the intercept of the H vs J curve. The slope of the H vs J plot also provides the value of series resistance. All of the diode parameters such as the ideality factor, barrier height, and series resistance are displayed in . The better ideality factor with a lower barrier height of the FTO/compound 1/Al device makes it more significant than the other device.

We have analyzed the J–V characteristic using the theory of space charge limited current (SCLC). It provides us an insightful view on the charge transport mechanism in the Schottky junction. In this regard, we have plotted the J–V characteristic into a semilogarithmic scale for both devices (d). We have found three distinguished regions which correspond to different conduction mechanism governed J–V characteristics. Region I in the low voltage regime indicates Ohmic conduction (J ∝ V). Region II which is observed in the intermediate voltage regime corresponds to the space charge limit current (SCLC) mechanism governed by shallow trapping states. Here, the current density varies as J ∝ V 2. In region III, the current density varies as J ∝ V n , where n is greater than 2. This region is also influenced by the SCLC mechanism, but the exponential distribution of traps plays the major role.

elements.content: We have measured the electron mobility, transit time, SCLC conductivity, and charge concentration values using the second region of J–V characteristics. According to Mott–Gurney, the current density under the SCLC mechanism followed as J = 9 μ e f f ε 0 ε r 8 ( V 2 d 3 ) where μeff is the effective mobility, ε0 is the permittivity of free space, and εr is the dielectric constant. The value of the dielectric constant is measured as 2.4 and 1.2 for compounds 1 and 2, respectively (Supporting Information). The value of μeff is derived from the slope of the J–V 2 plot which is displayed in e. We have also measured the transit time which signifies the time to reach from anode to cathode. The transit time (τ) of the charge carrier is derived from the following equation. The greater mobility with lower transit time of compound 1 makes the material more suitable for the optoelectronic device. τ = 9 ε 0 ε r 8 d ( V J )

elements.content: We have also measured the charge concentration (N) using the following equation N = σ SCLC q μ eff where σSCLC is the SCLC conductivity. The better charge concentration of compound 1 endorses the improvement in electrical parameters found from the above studies. All of the parameters of the charge transport mechanism for both devices are enlisted in . Here, due to the solid-state structural transformation via photochemical [2 + 2] cycloaddition, π···π stacking interactions among the adjacent chains have been eliminated in the dimerized product. As a result, the conductivity value is significantly reduced. This observation is in good agreement with our earlier report, where the conductivity has been enhanced upon photodimerization due to the increase in magnitude of π···π stacking interactions.

To shed light on the semiconducting properties of compounds 1 and 2, density functional theory (DFT) computations have been performed. The semiconducting behavior is realized by the band calculation, which is normally the difference between the energy of the highest occupied and lowest unoccupied molecular orbitals (ΔE = E LUMO – E HOMO, eV). Here, the theoretical band gaps of compounds 1 and 2 have been calculated as 3.52 and 3.77 eV, respectively (), which follow the observed trend of conductivity values obtained experimentally. Thus, the electrical nature of the compounds is well consistent with experimental findings.

Theoretical Studies

To shed light on the semiconducting properties of compounds 1 and 2, density functional theory (DFT) computations have been performed. The semiconducting behavior is realized by the band calculation, which is normally the difference between the energy of the highest occupied and lowest unoccupied molecular orbitals (ΔE = E LUMO - E HOMO, eV). Here, the theoretical band gaps of compounds 1 and 2 have been calculated as 3.52 and 3.77 eV, respectively (), which follow the observed trend of conductivity values obtained experimentally. Thus, the electrical nature of the compounds is well consistent with experimental findings.

elements.content: In summary, we have synthesized a Cd­(II) based ladder polymer which undergoes Br···π and π···π interactions to construct a 3D supramolecular architecture. The compound undergoes SCSC photochemical [2 + 2] cycloaddition reaction to generate a dimerized 1D CP. Here, the structural transformation eradicates the π···π stacking interactions present among the adjacent layers. This leads to the reduction of conductivity value after photodimerization. Thus, the material follows the “box open–box close” rule during the electrical conductivity, which may be a useful concept for material applications.
elements.clean_text:
Conclusions

In summary, we have synthesized a Cd(II) based ladder polymer which undergoes Br⋅⋅⋅π and π⋅⋅⋅π interactions to construct a 3D supramolecular architecture. The compound undergoes SCSC photochemical [2 + 2] cycloaddition reaction to generate a dimerized 1D CP. Here, the structural transformation eradicates the π⋅⋅⋅π stacking interactions present among the adjacent layers. This leads to the reduction of conductivity value after photodimerization. Thus, the material follows the "box open-box close" rule during the electrical conductivity, which may be a useful concept for material applications.

A solution of bpe (0.036 g, 0.2 mmol) in MeOH (2 mL) was slowly and carefully layered to a solution of Cd­(NO3)2·4H2O (0.062 g, 0.2 mmol), in H2O (2 mL) using 2 mL of buffer solution of DMF followed by layering of H2 p-brba (0. 0.040 g, 0.2 mmol) neutralized with Et3N (0.021 g, 0.2 mmol) in 2 mL of EtOH. Then, the resulting reaction mixture was kept in a dark cabinet. The colorless block-shaped crystals of [Cd­(bpe)­(p-brba)2] n (1) were obtained after a week (0.097 g, yield 70%). Elemental analysis (%) calcd for C26H18Br2CdN2O4: C, 44.95; H, 2.61; N, 4.03; found: C, 44.7; H, 2.4; N, 4.2. IR (KBr pellet, cm–1): 1610νas(COO–), 1391νsys(COO–). 1H NMR (300 MHz, d 6-DMSO, 298 K): δ = 8.59 (d, 4H, PyH), 7.94 (d, 4H, PhH), 7.60 (d, 4H, PyH), 7.54 (s, 2H, CHCH), 7.46 (d, 4H, PhH).

Conversion of 1 to 2: Light yellow block crystals of [Cd­(rctt-tpcb)1/2(p-brba)2] n (2) were obtained by UV irradiation of crystals of 1 for 30 min. C26H18Br2CdN2O4: C, 44.95; H, 2.61; N, 4.03; found: C, 44.5; H, 2.7; N, 4.1. IR (KBr pellet, cm–1): 1585νas(COO–), 1390νsys(COO–). 1H NMR (300 MHz, d 6-DMSO, 298 K): δ = 8.34 (d, 4H, PyH), 7.94 (d, 4H, PhH), 7.45 (d, 4H, PyH), 7.23 (d, 4H, PhH), 4.66 (s, 2H, CHCH).
